    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Offensive realism is a theory in international relations that seeks to explain how states behave in the global system. It was first introduced by John J. Mearsheimer in his book "The Tragedy of Great Power Politics".</p>
<p>According to offensive realism, states are primarily concerned with maximizing their own power and security in an anarchic international system where there is no hierarchical authority above them. The theory argues that states are inherently aggressive and seek to gain power at the expense of other states.</p>
<p>Offensive realists argue that states are rational actors driven by self-interest and constantly engage in offensive actions to ensure their own survival and increase their power relative to other states. They emphasize the importance of military capabilities, territorial expansion, and realpolitik in international relations.</p>
<p>The theory also contends that states are always uncertain about other states' intentions and thus tend to adopt a cautious and aggressive stance. This leads to a "security dilemma" where one state's defensive actions can be perceived as offensive by other states, leading to a spiral of arms race and conflict.</p>
<p>Offensive realism has been criticized for its pessimistic and grim view of international relations, as it assumes that war and conflict are inevitable as states pursue their own self-interest. Critics argue that it oversimplifies states' motivations and neglects other factors, such as economic interdependence and the role of international institutions, in shaping states' behavior.</p>
<p>Overall, offensive realism provides a theoretical framework for understanding how states pursue power and security in a competitive international system, but it is just one of many theories in international relations and does not capture the full complexity of states' motivations and actions.</p></div>

