son. Therefore, adequate HIV knowledge is critical for protecting young adolescents from HIV, as they are among the most vulnerable Badru et al. (2020).<br/><br/>Figure 1: HIV prevalence among young people aged 15-24 disaggregated by sex Source- Report of the Gender Assessment of the HIV Response in Nigeria 2022, UNAIDS (2021))<br/>The graph above clearly highlights that HIV prevalence among young women between the ages of 15- 24 is doubled that of you men between the ages of 15-24 (women 0.6 vs men 0.3) according to the report of the Gender Assessment of the HIV Response in Nigeria in 2022 support by UNAIDS (2021) data. There this intervention is clearly timely to address the infection and transmission rates.<br/><br/>Figure 1. Number of young people living with HIV aged 15-24 years disaggregated by sex (Source- Report of the Gender Assessment of the HIV Response in Nigeria 2022, UNAIDS (2021))<br/>According to the table above young women between the ages of 15 -24 living with HIV account for two-thirds (63%) of young people living with HIV (110,000 vs 64,000) according to the report of the Gender Assessment of the HIV Response in Nigeria in 2022 support by UNAIDS (2021) data.<br/><br/>Figure 3: Comprehensive knowledge of HIV in different populations NDHS (2018)<br/>The National Demographic Health Survey of 2018 also highlights the significant knowledge gap on HIV by the target population which stood at 38.5. Considering the age of the target population, this is considerably on the high side and constitutes a significant public health challenge that would require immediate intervention, NDHS (2018).<br/>The proposed school-based program for Youths to prevent HIV in Nigeria can be linked to theoretical frameworks and intervention mapping in public health behaviour change intervention design. The program&#x27;s design and implementation would align with the Social and Behavior Change Communication (SBCC) framework, which emphasizes the importance of addressing knowledge, attitudes, and behaviours related to HIV prevention (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004). The program would also incorporate peer education, which is consistent with the Diffusion of Innovations theory, which posits that behaviour change is more likely to occur when individuals receive information from peers who share similar characteristics Arije et al. (2023).<br/>Constraints for the intervention, such as limited funding and cultural and religious beliefs, can be addressed using intervention mapping. For example, the program&#x27;s design would be tailored to be culturally sensitive and appropriate, and community leaders can be involved in the program&#x27;s development and implementation to ensure its success and sustainability (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004) (Chizoba et al., 2020).<br/>Needs assessment, logic model of the problem. <br/>The need assessment would be conducted to identify the factors that predispose young adults to HIV transmission, such as lack of adequate knowledge about HIV, attitudes, beliefs, and behaviours related to HIV prevention Hart (2011) Theunissen et al. (2013). This would also be used to identify the environmental, and  social, factors that contribute to HIV transmission among young adults and strategies would be developed to address these factors(Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004) (Chizoba et al., 2020).<br/>Based on the needs assessment, the program&#x27;s objectives, design, and implementation would be tailored to address the identified factors and ensure the program&#x27;s success and sustainability. For example, the program can incorporate peer education to address knowledge gaps and attitudes related to HIV prevention, community engagement to address environmental and social factors, and policy advocacy to address policy factors that contribute to the high prevalence of HIV among Nigerian Youths Arije et al. (2023). (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004) (Chizoba et al., 2020) (Kim et al., 2022).<br/><br/>Figure 4: Logic Model of Problem for Preventing HIV among Youths in Nigeria<br/>Behavioural factors affecting HIV prevention among Youths include inadequate knowledge about HIV transmission and prevention methods, misconceptions about the disease, and low condom use during sexual encounters. A study in Nigeria found that more than half of the respondents (53.9%) reported not using a condom in their last sexual encounter (O et al., 2013). Additionally, the willingness to pay for HIV prevention commodities, such as condoms, among key population groups can influence the accessibility and utilization of these commodities (Durosinmi-Etti et al., 2022). <br/>Furthermore, cultural factors and social stigma surrounding HIV and sexual health discussions can also impact the effectiveness of prevention efforts (Iwelunmor et al., 2014) and limited access to prevention resources. <br/>To address these factors, it is essential to provide accurate information, promote open discussions, create supportive environments for Youths to make informed decisions about their sexual health and provide adequate infrastructural facilities and trained human resources providing services.<br/>Program outcomes and objectives; Logic model of change <br/>The program objectives for the proposed school-based program for youths to prevent HIV in Nigeria are to increase knowledge, attitudes, and behaviours related to HIV prevention among Nigerian teens. The program aims to address the knowledge gap and behaviour risks related to HIV among adolescents and young adults in Nigeria (Okudo, 2014) (Chizoba et al., 2020).<br/>The program objectives will be achieved through a combination of evidence-based behaviour change interventions, including peer education, tailored, innovative, and adaptive HIV prevention solutions, and community engagement (Maduakolam et al., 2022) (Chizoba et al., 2020). The program will also promote the uptake of HIV testing and counselling services, as well as the use of HIV self-testing kits Arije et 