s approach will help to help ensure that the program is culturally appropriate, relevant, and sustainable in the long term.<br/>Diffusion theory, on the other hand, would focuse on the spread of innovations and ideas through social networks. Leveraging existing social networks among Nigerian Youths teachers, and peer educators, the program can increase its reach and impact. Peer-led discussions and group activities can help promote positive social norms around HIV prevention and encourage healthy behaviors.<br/>The implementation strategy will involve a phased approach to ensure the program&#x27;s success and sustainability and will involve the following steps:<br/>Establish partnerships with local stakeholders, including schools, health professionals, and community organizations.<br/>Train teachers and peer educators on the program&#x27;s content and delivery methods, using the behaviour change matrix and communication methods/practical applications.<br/>Launch the program in selected schools, with ongoing support and supervision provided by the program team.<br/>Encourage peer-led discussions and group activities to promote positive social norms and healthy behaviours.<br/>Monitor the program&#x27;s progress through regular check-ins with teachers, peer educators, and school administrators.<br/>Establish a feedback loop to continuously improve the program based on the experiences and outcomes of the participants.<br/>Evaluate the program&#x27;s effectiveness using a pre-post design, as described in the evaluation plan.<br/>If successful, scale up the program to additional schools and, adapting the intervention as needed to suit different contexts.<br/>By incorporating the linkage approach and diffusion theory into the implementation strategy, the school-based HIV prevention program can maximize its impact and sustainability in addressing the health behaviour problem among Nigerian Youths (Meyer, Louder and Nicolas, 2021) <br/>Evaluation plan <br/>The evaluation plan for the school-based HIV prevention program will include both process and effect evaluations. The process evaluation will assess the completeness and fidelity of the program&#x27;s implementation, including context, reach, dose delivered, dose received, and recruitment. The process evaluation will use both qualitative and quantitative methods, such as surveys, interviews, and focus groups with teachers, peer educators, and students. The frequency of assessment will depend on the specific variable being assessed.<br/>The effect evaluation will focus on the specific behaviour change objectives identified in the behaviour change matrix. The effect evaluation will be determinant/change objective-based, measuring changes in knowledge, attitudes, skills, social norms, and access related to HIV prevention. The instruments used to assess the program&#x27;s impact may include questionnaires and Likert scales, which may require cultural adaptations to ensure their appropriateness and relevance to the Nigerian context (Finkbeiner et al., 2013) (Falconi‐McCahill, Lee and Knights, 2022)<br/>Discussion / Implications of the Intervention / Future Research and Limitations <br/>One limitation of the evaluation plan is the lack of a control group, which may limit the ability to attribute changes in behaviour and health outcomes solely to the program. However, the use of a pre-post design and the inclusion of multiple variables in the process evaluation can help strengthen the evaluation&#x27;s internal validity.<br/>The evaluation plan for the school-based HIV prevention program is informed by similar evaluation plans for other sexual health and HIV prevention programs, such as those described in the search results of ((Finkbeiner et al., 2013) (Falconi‐McCahill, Lee and Knights, 2022) (Zango, Crutzen and de Vries, 2021) (Mustanski et al., 2020) (Mustanski et al., 2020a)). These evaluation plans emphasize the importance of assessing both process and effect evaluations, usin