    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Introduction</p>
<p>The high prevalence of HIV among Nigerian youth aged 15-24, particularly adolescent girls and young women, poses a substantial public health concern. Various factors, such as multiple concurrent sexual relationships, transgenerational sex, and transactional sex, contribute to their vulnerability to HIV, influenced by sociocultural contexts that differ across the country. Research indicates that adolescents account for about 7% of the total number of individuals with HIV in Nigeria, with young women disproportionately affected compared to their male counterparts (Arije et al. 2023). Consequently, there is an urgent need to address this health behavior problem through targeted interventions tailored to this population's specific needs and challenges.</p>
<p>The proposed school-based program for preventing HIV among Nigerian youths will be guided by theoretical frameworks and intervention mapping, focusing on evidence-based behavior change interventions. The Social and Behavior Change Communication (SBCC), Diffusion of Innovations theory, and the Health Belief Model form the basis for the intervention design (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004; Arije et al. 2023). These frameworks have previously guided successful interventions in Nigeria and other similar locations, highlighting the potential for effective implementation and impact.</p>
<p>The SBCC framework emphasizes the importance of addressing knowledge, attitudes, and behaviors related to HIV prevention (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004). Through targeted communication and strategic behavior change techniques, the intervention will aim to improve youths' knowledge about HIV transmission and prevention, enhance positive attitudes towards HIV prevention, and promote protective behaviors. In contrast, the Diffusion of Innovations theory underscores the significance of leveraging social networks and involving peers in disseminating information and promoting positive norms regarding HIV prevention (Arije et al. 2023). Peer education, a crucial component of the proposed intervention, is consistent with this approach, fostering long-term behavior changes among high-risk HIV groups (He et al. 2020).</p>
<p>Several constraints could impede the implementation and effectiveness of the proposed intervention, such as cultural and religious beliefs, political barriers, or limited funding. Addressing these constraints requires a comprehensive intervention mapping approach, involving a systematic process of program planning, design, implementation, and evaluation in accordance with local contexts (Gallant and Maticka-Tyndale, 2004). By involving community leaders and local stakeholders in the development and implementation of the program, the intervention can be tailored to be culturally sensitive and contextually appropriate, ensuring its success and sustainability (Chizoba et al., 2020).</p>
<p>Furthermore, the Health Belief Model provides valuable insight into factors influencing individuals' decisions to adopt protective behaviors related to HIV prevention, such as perceived susceptibility, perceived severity, perceived benefits, perceived barriers, and self-efficacy (Rosenstock, 1974). By addressing these factors, the intervention will not only impart knowledge and skills but also target the cognitive determinants associated with HIV risk behaviors among Nigerian youths.</p>
<p>Given the complex nature of the health behavior problem and various sociocultural factors influencing HIV prevalence among Nigerian youths, the proposed intervention seeks a holistic approach by incorporating multiple components tailored to the target population. The program's components will include peer education, innovative and adaptive HIV prevention solutions, school-based sexual and reproductive health education, and community engagement initiatives that address the gendered nature of HIV vulnerability (Arije et al. 2023).</p>
<p>In conclusion, the proposed school-based program for preventing HIV among Nigerian youths demonstrates great potential to address the significant public health challenge of HIV prevalence in this population. By leveraging evidence-based behavior change interventions and engaging youth in the design and implementation process, along with considering potential constraints and employing sound theoretical frameworks, the intervention aims to make a significant and sustainable impact on the lives of the most vulnerable Nigerian youths.</p></div>

